# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: calcium-carbide
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] In chemistry, an **acetylide** is a compound that can be viewed as the result of replacing one or both hydrogen atoms of acetylene (ethyne) HC≡CH by metallic or other cations.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Calcium carbide is an important industrial compound, which has long been used to produce acetylene for welding and illumination.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] It is also a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Other acetylides are reagents in organic synthesis.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] It applies to an acetylene RC≡CM, where R = H or a side chain that is usually organic.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] The nomenclature can be ambiguous with regards to the distinction between compounds of the types MC2R and M2C2.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] When both hydrogens of acetylene are replaced by metals, the compound can also be called carbide, e.g., calcium carbide Ca2+[−C≡C−], which is calcium acetylide.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] When only one hydrogen atom is replaced, the anion may be called **hydrogen acetylide** or the prefix *mono*- may be attached to the metal, as in monosodium acetylide or sodium hydrogen acetylide, Na+[−C≡CH].
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Metal acetylide may be described as salts, but that description rarely comports with crystallographic analysis.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] In the absence of additional ligands, metal acetylides adopt polymeric structures wherein the acetylide groups are bridging ligands.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Alkali metal acetylides have the general formula [M2C2 (M = Li, Na, K, etc).They are sometimes represented as [M+]2[−C≡C−] but the C---M bonding might also be described as polar covalent.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] They dissolve without decomposition in ammonia.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Such solutions are proposed to contain solvated −C≡C− ions.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Alkali metal and alkaline earth metal acetylides have the general formula [M'C2 (M' = Mg, Ca, etc).
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Rather than salt-like, they can be considered Zintl phase compounds, containing −C≡C− ions, with a triple bond between the two carbon atoms.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] The −C≡C− ion has a closed shell ground state of 1Σ+ g, making it isoelectronic to a neutral molecule N2, which may afford it some gas-phase stability.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Acetylides of the transition metals, show evidence of covalent character, e. g. for being neither dissolved nor decomposed by water and by radically different chemical reactions.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Even the stoichiometrically simple silver acetylide and copper acetylide appear highly covalent.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] The inventory of such complexes numbers in the hundreds.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] The acetylide π* antibonding orbitals are generally too high-energy for substantial metal-ligand backbonding, but still do hybridize with the metal *d* orbitals.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Consequently metal-to-ligand charge transfer excitations lie at low levels in the compounds' spectra.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Monopotassium and monosodium acetylide can be prepared by reacting acetylene with bases like sodium amide or with the elemental metals, often at room temperature and atmospheric pressure.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Copper(I) acetylide can be prepared by passing acetylene through an aqueous solution of copper(I) chloride because of a low solubility equilibrium.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Similarly, silver acetylides can be obtained from silver nitrate.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] In organic synthesis, acetylides are usually prepared by treating acetylene and alkynes with organometallic or inorganic bases.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Classically, liquid ammonia was used as solvent for deprotonations, but ethers are now more commonly used.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Calcium carbide is prepared industrially by heating carbon with lime (calcium oxide) at approximately 2,000 °C.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] A similar process can be used to produce lithium carbide.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Dilithium acetylide, Li2C2, competes with the preparation of the monolithium derivative LiC2H.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Acetylides of the type RC≡CM are widely used in alkynylations in organic chemistry.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] They are nucleophiles that add to a variety of electrophilic and unsaturated substrates.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] A classic application is the Favorskii reaction, such as in the sequence shown below.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Here ethyl propiolate is deprotonated by *n*-butyllithium to give the corresponding lithium acetylide.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] This acetylide adds to the carbonyl center of cyclopentanone.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Hydrolysis liberates the alkynyl alcohol.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] The dimerization of acetylene to vinylacetylene proceeds by insertion of acetylene into a copper(I) acetylide complex.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] The copper-catalyzed Click reaction of terminal alkynes and azides proceeds via copper(I) acetylide intermediates.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Acetylides are sometimes used as intermediates in coupling reactions.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Examples include Sonogashira coupling, Cadiot-Chodkiewicz coupling, Glaser coupling and Eglinton coupling.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Some acetylides are notoriously explosive.
[src:calcium-carbide/acetylide] Formation of acetylides poses a risk in handling of gaseous acetylene in presence of metals such as mercury, silver or copper, or alloys with their high content (brass, bronze, silver solder).
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] The ***Algemeen Dagblad*** (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈɑlɣəmeːn ˈdɑɣblɑt]; lit.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] 'General Daily Paper'), also known by its initialism ***AD*** ([aːˈdeː]), is a Dutch daily newspaper based in Rotterdam.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] Founded in 1946, *Algemeen Dagblad* is published in tabloid format and headquartered in Rotterdam.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] Its regional focus includes the cities and regions around Rotterdam, Utrecht and The Hague.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] In South Holland and Utrecht, it is published and distributed with local dailies.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] The national edition is for sale in every city in the Netherlands and distributed throughout the rest of the country.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] *AD* is owned and published by DPG Media, known as De Persgroep until 2019 and previously PCM Uitgevers.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] In the period of 1995–96, *Algemeen Dagblad* had a circulation of 401,000 copies, making it the second best-selling paper in the Netherlands.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] In 2013, the paper was the second largest paid newspaper of the Netherlands after *De Telegraaf*.
[src:calcium-carbide/algemeen-dagblad] After a merger with seven regional newspapers on 1 September 2005 and ongoing reduction in readership, it had an average circulation merger of 365,912 copies in 2014.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide is prepared by direct reaction of aluminium and carbon in an electric arc furnace.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] An alternative reaction begins with alumina, but it is less favorable because of generation of carbon monoxide.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Silicon carbide also reacts with aluminium to yield Al4C3.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] This conversion limits the mechanical applications of SiC, because Al4C3 is more brittle than SiC.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide hydrolyses with evolution of methane and considerable amounts of heat.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] The addition of 10g of Al4C3 to 10g of water was found to reach a maximum temperature of 387 °F (197 °C) at a time of 11 minutes in one study, while in another the addition of 20g of Al4C3 to 10g of water reached a maximum temperature of 280 °F (138 °C).
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Reversing the order and adding 10g of water to 20g of Al4C3 reached a maximum temperature of 349 °F (176 °C).
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] This tendency can be decreased by coating the silicon carbide particles with a suitable oxide or nitride, preoxidation of the particles to form a silica coating, or using a layer of sacrificial metal.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] An aluminium-aluminium carbide composite material can be made by mechanical alloying, by mixing aluminium powder with graphite particles.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide has an unusual crystal structure that consists of alternating layers of Al2C and Al2C2.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Each aluminium atom is coordinated to 4 carbon atoms to give a tetrahedral arrangement.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Carbon atoms exist in 2 different binding environments; one is a deformed octahedron of 6 Al atoms at a distance of 217 pm.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] The other is a distorted trigonal bipyramidal structure of 4 Al atoms at 190–194 pm and a fifth Al atom at 221 pm.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Small amounts of aluminium carbide are a common impurity of technical calcium carbide.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] In electrolytic manufacturing of aluminium, aluminium carbide forms as a corrosion product of the graphite electrodes.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] In metal matrix composites based on aluminium matrix reinforced with non-metal carbides (silicon carbide, boron carbide, etc.) or carbon fibres, aluminium carbide often forms as an unwanted product.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] In case of carbon fibre, it reacts with the aluminium matrix at temperatures above 500 °C (932 °F); better wetting of the fibre and inhibition of chemical reaction can be achieved by coating it with e.g. titanium boride.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide particles finely dispersed in aluminium matrix lower the tendency of the material to creep, especially in combination with silicon carbide particles.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide can be used as an abrasive in high-speed cutting tools.
[src:calcium-carbide/aluminium-carbide] It has approximately the same hardness as topaz.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] An **ion** (/ˈaɪ.ɒn, -ən/) is an atom or molecule with a net electrical charge.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The charge of an electron is considered to be negative by convention and this charge is equal and opposite to the charge of a proton, which is considered to be positive by convention.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The net charge of an ion is not zero because its total number of electrons is unequal to its total number of protons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] A **cation** is a positively charged ion with fewer electrons than protons (e.g.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] K+ (potassium ion)) while an **anion** is a negatively charged ion with more electrons than protons (e.g.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Cl− (chloride ion) and OH− (hydroxide ion)).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Opposite electric charges are pulled towards one another by electrostatic force, so cations and anions attract each other and readily form ionic compounds.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ions consisting of only a single atom are termed *monatomic ions*, *atomic ions* or *simple ions*, while ions consisting of two or more atoms are termed polyatomic ions or *molecular ions*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The net charge of an ion is indicated as a superscript on the right.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] To indicate a +1 or −1 charge, only a + or − is written respectively, as seen in Na+ (sodium ion) and F− (fluoride ion).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] To indicate a more severe charge, the number of additional or missing electrons is supplied, as seen in O2− 2 (peroxide, negatively charged, polyatomic) and He2+ (alpha particle, positively charged, monatomic).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] In the case of physical ionization in a fluid (gas or liquid), "ion pairs" are created by spontaneous molecule collisions, where each generated pair consists of a free electron and a positive ion.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ions are also created by chemical interactions, such as the dissolution of a salt in liquids, or by other means, such as passing a direct current through a conducting solution, dissolving an anode via ionization.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The word *ion* was coined from neuter present participle of Greek ἰέναι (*ienai*), meaning "to go".
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] A cation is something that moves down (Greek: κάτω, *kato*, meaning "down") and an anion is something that moves up (Greek: ἄνω, *ano*, meaning "up").
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] They are so called because ions move toward the electrode of opposite charge.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This term was introduced (after a suggestion by the English polymath William Whewell) by English physicist and chemist Michael Faraday in 1834 for the then-unknown species that *goes* from one electrode to the other through an aqueous medium.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Faraday did not know the nature of these species, but he knew that since metals dissolved into and entered a solution at one electrode and new metal came forth from a solution at the other electrode; that some kind of substance has moved through the solution in a current.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This conveys matter from one place to the other.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] In correspondence with Faraday, Whewell also coined the words *anode* and *cathode*, as well as *anion* and *cation* as ions that are attracted to the respective electrodes.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Svante Arrhenius put forth, in his 1884 dissertation, the explanation of the fact that solid crystalline salts dissociate into paired charged particles when dissolved, for which he would win the 1903 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Arrhenius' explanation was that in forming a solution, the salt dissociates into Faraday's ions, he proposed that ions formed even in the absence of an electric current.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ions in their gas-like state are highly reactive and will rapidly interact with ions of opposite charge to give neutral molecules or ionic salts.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ions are also produced in the liquid or solid state when salts interact with solvents (for example, water) to produce solvation shell around them.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] These *solvated ions* are more stable, for reasons involving a combination of energy and entropy changes as the ions move away from each other to interact with the liquid.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] These stabilized species are more commonly found in the environment at low temperatures.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] A common example is the ions present in seawater, which are derived from dissolved salts.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] As charged objects, ions are attracted to opposite electric charges (positive to negative, and vice versa) and repelled by like charges.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] When they move, their trajectories can be deflected by a magnetic field.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Electrons, due to their smaller mass and thus larger space-filling properties as matter waves, determine the size of atoms and molecules that possess any electrons at all.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Thus, anions (negatively charged ions) are larger than the parent molecule or atom, as the excess electron(s) repel each other and add to the physical size of the ion, because its size is determined by its electron cloud.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Cations are smaller than the corresponding parent atom or molecule due to the smaller size of the electron cloud.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] One particular cation (that of hydrogen) contains no electrons, and thus consists of a single proton – *much smaller* than the parent hydrogen atom.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Since the electric charge on a proton is equal in magnitude to the charge on an electron, the net electric charge on an ion is equal to the number of protons in the ion minus the number of electrons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] An anion (−) (/ˈænˌaɪ.ən/ *ANN-eye-ən*, from the Greek word ἄνω (*ánō*), meaning "up") is an ion with more electrons than protons, giving it a net negative charge (since electrons are negatively charged and protons are positively charged).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] A cation (+) (/ˈkætˌaɪ.ən/ *KAT-eye-ən*, from the Greek word κάτω (*kátō*), meaning "down") is an ion with fewer electrons than protons, giving it a positive charge.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] There are additional names used for ions with multiple charges.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] For example, an ion with a −2 charge is known as a dianion and an ion with a +2 charge is known as a dication.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] A zwitterion is a neutral molecule with positive and negative charges at different locations within that molecule.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Cations and anions are measured by their ionic radius and they differ in relative size: "Cations are small, most of them less than 10−10 m (10−8 cm) in radius.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] But most anions are large, as is the most common Earth anion, oxygen.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The terms *anion* and *cation* (for ions that respectively travel to the anode and cathode during electrolysis) were introduced by Michael Faraday in 1834 following his consultation with William Whewell.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ions are ubiquitous in nature and are responsible for diverse phenomena from the luminescence of the Sun to the existence of the Earth's ionosphere.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Atoms in their ionic state may have a different color from neutral atoms, and thus light absorption by metal ions gives the color of gemstones.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ions can be non-chemically prepared using various ion sources, usually involving high voltage or temperature.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] These are used in a multitude of devices such as mass spectrometers, optical emission spectrometers, particle accelerators, ion implanters, and ion engines.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] As reactive charged particles, they are also used in air purification by disrupting microbes, and in household items such as smoke detectors.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] As signalling and metabolism in organisms are controlled by a precise ionic gradient across membranes, the disruption of this gradient contributes to cell death.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This is a common mechanism exploited by natural and artificial biocides, including the ion channels gramicidin and amphotericin (a fungicide).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Inorganic dissolved ions are a component of total dissolved solids, a widely known indicator of water quality.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The ionizing effect of radiation on a gas is extensively used for the detection of radiation such as alpha, beta, gamma, and X-rays.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The original ionization event in these instruments results in the formation of an "ion pair"; a positive ion and a free electron, by ion impact by the radiation on the gas molecules.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The ionization chamber is the simplest of these detectors, and collects all the charges created by *direct ionization* within the gas through the application of an electric field.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] When writing the chemical formula for an ion , its net charge is written in superscript immediately after the chemical structure for the molecule/atom.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The net charge is written with the magnitude *before* the sign; that is, a doubly charged cation is indicated as **2+** instead of **+2**.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] However, the magnitude of the charge is omitted for singly charged molecules/atoms; for example, the sodium cation is indicated as Na+ and *not* Na1+.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] An alternative (and acceptable) way of showing a molecule/atom with multiple charges is by drawing out the signs multiple times, this is often seen with transition metals.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Chemists sometimes circle the sign; this is merely ornamental and does not alter the chemical meaning.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] All three representations of Fe2+, Fe++, and Fe⊕⊕ shown in the figure, are thus equivalent.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Monatomic ions are sometimes also denoted with Roman numerals, particularly in spectroscopy; for example, the Fe2+ (positively doubly charged) example seen above is referred to as Fe(III), FeIII or Fe III (Fe I for a neutral Fe atom, Fe II for a singly ionized Fe ion).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The Roman numeral designates the *formal oxidation state* of an element, whereas the superscripted Indo-Arabic numerals denote the net charge.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The two notations are, therefore, exchangeable for monatomic ions, but the Roman numerals *cannot* be applied to polyatomic ions.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] However, it is possible to mix the notations for the individual metal centre with a polyatomic complex, as shown by the uranyl ion example.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] If an ion contains unpaired electrons, it is called a *radical* ion.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Just like uncharged radicals, radical ions are very reactive.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Polyatomic ions containing oxygen, such as carbonate and sulfate, are called *oxyanions*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Molecular ions that contain at least one carbon to hydrogen bond are called *organic ions*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] If the charge in an organic ion is formally centred on a carbon, it is termed a *carbocation* (if positively charged) or *carbanion* (if negatively charged).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Monatomic ions are formed by the gain or loss of electrons to the valence shell (the outer-most electron shell) in an atom .
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The inner shells of an atom are filled with electrons that are tightly bound to the positively charged atomic nucleus, and so do not participate in this kind of chemical interaction.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The process of gaining or losing electrons from a neutral atom or molecule is called *ionization*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Atoms can be ionized by bombardment with radiation, but the more usual process of ionization encountered in chemistry is the transfer of electrons between atoms or molecules.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This transfer is usually driven by the attaining of stable ("closed shell") electronic configurations.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Atoms will gain or lose electrons depending on which action takes the least energy.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] For example, a sodium atom, Na, has a single electron in its valence shell, surrounding two stable, filled inner shells of 2 and 8 electrons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] On the other hand, a chlorine atom, Cl, has 7 electrons in its valence shell, which is one short of the stable, filled shell with 8 electrons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This driving force is what causes sodium and chlorine to undergo a chemical reaction, wherein the "extra" electron is transferred from sodium to chlorine, forming sodium cations and chloride anions.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Being oppositely charged, these cations and anions form ionic bonds and combine to form sodium chloride, NaCl, more commonly known as table salt.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Polyatomic and molecular ions are often formed by the gaining or losing of elemental ions such as a proton, H+, in neutral molecules.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] For example, when ammonia, NH3, accepts a proton, H+—a process called protonation—it forms the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ammonia and ammonium have the same number of electrons in essentially the same electronic configuration, but ammonium has an extra proton that gives it a net positive charge.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Ammonia can also lose an electron to gain a positive charge, forming the ion NH+3.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] However, this ion is unstable, because it has an incomplete valence shell around the nitrogen atom, making it a very reactive radical ion.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Due to the instability of radical ions, polyatomic and molecular ions are usually formed by gaining or losing elemental ions such as H+, rather than gaining or losing electrons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This allows the molecule to preserve its stable electronic configuration while acquiring an electrical charge.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Liquids with low dielectric constant (below 10) are not quite suitable for ions formation for several reasons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] First of all, electrostatic attraction between cation and anion is much stronger than in water, which requires well developed solvating layer for preventing their immediate reaggregation.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] However, molecules of nonpolar liquids cannot create such layer due to lack of dipole moments.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] In addition, many electrolytes are not soluble in nonpolar liquids.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Nevertheless, pioneering works by Onsager, Fuoss, Kraus in 20th century proved that ionization in nonpolar liquids is possible.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Recent series of studies conducted by Dukhin and Parlia with wide variety of liquids and solutes confirmed this conclusion and allowed formulation of the following concept for ionization in non-polar liquids, which is distinctively different from aqueous solutions.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The solute substance must be amphiphile consisting of hydrophobic tail and polar head in order to create ions in nonpolar liquid.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Existence of hydrophobic tail ensures solubility.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Existence of polar head provides source for initial ions creation by dissociation.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The most peculiar feature is formation of solvation layer around ions almost immediately after dissociation.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Solvent molecules cannot build up such solvating layers.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] However, the neutral molecules of the solute do have some dipole moments at their polar heads.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] These dipoles would be attracted by primary ions right after dissociation.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This attraction creates a layer of the neutral solute molecules around central ions, which can be considered as solvation layer.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Such solvated ions look like charged inverse micelles.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Basically, solute amphiphilic molecules in nonpolar liquids are source of both, dissociation and self-solvation, which distinguishes this ionization from aqueous solutions dramatically.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This concept led to creation of conductivity (non-aqueous) theory that fits experimental data for wide variety of nonpolar systems within up to 7 orders of magnitude.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The energy required to detach an electron in its lowest energy state from an atom or molecule of a gas with less net electric charge is called the *ionization potential*, or *ionization energy*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The *n*th ionization energy of an atom is the energy required to detach its *n*th electron after the first *n* − 1 electrons have already been detached.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Each successive ionization energy is markedly greater than the last.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Particularly great increases occur after any given block of atomic orbitals is exhausted of electrons.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] For this reason, ions tend to form in ways that leave them with full orbital blocks.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] For example, sodium has one *valence electron* in its outermost shell, so in ionized form it is commonly found with one lost electron, as Na+.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] On the other side of the periodic table, chlorine has seven valence electrons, so in ionized form it is commonly found with one gained electron, as Cl−.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Caesium has the lowest measured ionization energy of all the elements and helium has the greatest.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] In general, the ionization energy of metals is much lower than the ionization energy of nonmetals, which is why, in general, metals will lose electrons to form positively charged ions and nonmetals will gain electrons to form negatively charged ions.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] The most common type of ionic bonding is seen in compounds of metals and nonmetals (except noble gases, which rarely form chemical compounds).
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Metals are characterized by having a small number of electrons in excess of a stable, closed-shell electronic configuration.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] As such, they have the tendency to lose these extra electrons in order to attain a stable configuration.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This property is known as *electropositivity*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] Non-metals, on the other hand, are characterized by having an electron configuration just a few electrons short of a stable configuration.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] As such, they have the tendency to gain more electrons in order to achieve a stable configuration.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This tendency is known as *electronegativity*.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] When a highly electropositive metal is combined with a highly electronegative nonmetal, the extra electrons from the metal atoms are transferred to the electron-deficient nonmetal atoms.
[src:calcium-carbide/anions] This reaction produces metal cations and nonmetal anions, which are attracted to each other to form a *salt*.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:calcium-carbide/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In its standard state arsine is a colorless, denser-than-air gas that is slightly soluble in water (2% at 20 °C) and in many organic solvents as well.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Arsine itself is odorless, but it oxidizes in air and this creates a slight garlic or fish-like scent when the compound is present above 0.5 ppm.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This compound is kinetically stable: at room temperature it decomposes only slowly.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] 230 °C, decomposition to arsenic and hydrogen is sufficiently rapid to be the basis of the Marsh test for arsenic presence.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Similar to stibine, the decomposition of arsine is autocatalytic, as the arsenic freed during the reaction acts as a catalyst for the same reaction.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Several other factors, such as humidity, presence of light and certain catalysts (namely alumina) facilitate the rate of decomposition.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] AsH3 is a trigonal pyramidal molecule with H–As–H angles of 91.8° and three equivalent As–H bonds, each of 1.519 Å length.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] AsH3 is generally prepared by the reaction of As3+ sources with H− equivalents.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] As reported in 1775, Carl Scheele reduced arsenic(III) oxide with zinc in the presence of acid.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This reaction is a prelude to the Marsh test.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Alternatively, sources of As3− react with protonic reagents to also produce this gas.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The understanding of the chemical properties of AsH3 is well developed and can be anticipated based on an average of the behavior of pnictogen counterparts, such as PH3 and SbH3.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Typical for a heavy hydride (e.g., SbH3, H2Te, SnH4), AsH3 is unstable with respect to its elements.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In other words, it is stable kinetically but not thermodynamically.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This decomposition reaction is the basis of the Marsh test, which detects elemental As.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Arsine will react violently in presence of strong oxidizing agents, such as potassium permanganate, sodium hypochlorite, or nitric acid.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] AsH3 is used as a precursor to metal complexes of "naked" (or "nearly naked") arsenic.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] An example is the dimanganese species [(C5H5)Mn(CO)2]2AsH, wherein the Mn2AsH core is planar.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] A characteristic test for arsenic involves the reaction of AsH3 with Ag+, called the Gutzeit test for arsenic (see Sanger–Black apparatus for more).
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Although this test has become obsolete in analytical chemistry, the underlying reactions further illustrate the affinity of AsH3 for "soft" metal cations.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In the Gutzeit test, AsH3 is generated by reduction of aqueous arsenic compounds, typically arsenites, with Zn in the presence of H2SO4.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The evolved gaseous AsH3 is then exposed to AgNO3 either as powder or as a solution.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] With solid AgNO3, AsH3 reacts to produce yellow Ag4AsNO3, whereas AsH3 reacts with a solution of AgNO3 to give black Ag3As.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The acidic properties of the As–H bond are often exploited.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Upon reaction with the aluminium trialkyls, AsH3 gives the trimeric [R2AlAsH2]3, where R = (CH3)3C.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This reaction is relevant to the mechanism by which GaAs forms from AsH3 (see below).
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] AsH3 is generally considered non-basic, but it can be protonated by superacids to give isolable salts of the tetrahedral species [AsH4]+.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Reactions of arsine with the halogens (fluorine and chlorine) or some of their compounds, such as nitrogen trichloride, are extremely dangerous and can result in explosions.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In contrast to the behavior of PH3, AsH3 does not form stable chains, although diarsine (or diarsane) H2As–AsH2, and even triarsane H2As–As(H)–AsH2 have been detected.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] AsH3 is used in the synthesis of semiconducting materials related to microelectronics and solid-state lasers.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Related to phosphorus, arsenic is an n-dopant for silicon and germanium.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] For microelectronic applications, arsine can be provided by a sub-atmospheric gas source (a source that supplies less than atmospheric pressure).
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In this type of gas package, the arsine is adsorbed on a solid microporous adsorbent inside a gas cylinder.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This method allows the gas to be stored without pressure, significantly reducing the risk of an arsine gas leak from the cylinder.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] With this apparatus, arsine is obtained by applying vacuum to the gas cylinder valve outlet.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] For semiconductor manufacturing, this method is feasible, as processes such as ion implantation operate under high vacuum.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Since before WWII AsH3 was proposed as a possible chemical warfare weapon.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The gas is colorless, almost odorless, and 2.5 times denser than air, as required for a blanketing effect sought in chemical warfare.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] It is also lethal in concentrations far lower than those required to smell its garlic-like scent.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In spite of these characteristics, arsine was never officially used as a weapon, because of its high flammability and its lower efficacy when compared to the non-flammable alternative phosgene.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] On the other hand, several organic compounds based on arsine, such as lewisite (β-chlorovinyldichloroarsine), adamsite (diphenylaminechloroarsine), Clark 1 (diphenylchloroarsine) and Clark 2 (diphenylcyanoarsine) have been effectively developed for use in chemical warfare.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] AsH3 is well known in forensic science because it is a chemical intermediate in the detection of arsenic poisoning.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The old (but extremely sensitive) Marsh test generates AsH3 in the presence of arsenic.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This procedure, published in 1836 by James Marsh, is based upon treating an As-containing sample of a victim's body (typically the stomach contents) with As-free zinc and dilute sulfuric acid: if the sample contains arsenic, gaseous arsine will form.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The gas is swept into a glass tube and decomposed by means of heating around 250–300 °C.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The presence of As is indicated by formation of a deposit in the heated part of the equipment.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] On the other hand, the appearance of a black mirror deposit in the *cool* part of the equipment indicates the presence of antimony (the highly unstable SbH3 decomposes even at low temperatures).
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The Marsh test was widely used by the end of the 19th century and the start of the 20th; nowadays more sophisticated techniques such as atomic spectroscopy, inductively coupled plasma, and x-ray fluorescence analysis are employed in the forensic field.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Though neutron activation analysis was used to detect trace levels of arsenic in the mid 20th century, it has since fallen out of use in modern forensics.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The toxicity of arsine is distinct from that of other arsenic compounds.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The main route of exposure is by inhalation, although poisoning after skin contact has also been described.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Arsine attacks hemoglobin in the red blood cells, causing them to be destroyed by the body.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] The first signs of exposure, which can take several hours to become apparent, are headaches, vertigo, and nausea, followed by the symptoms of haemolytic anaemia (high levels of unconjugated bilirubin), haemoglobinuria and nephropathy.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In severe cases, the damage to the kidneys can be long-lasting.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Exposure to arsine concentrations of 250 ppm is rapidly fatal: concentrations of 25–30 ppm are fatal for 30 min exposure, and concentrations of 10 ppm can be fatal at longer exposure times.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Symptoms of poisoning appear after exposure to concentrations of 0.5 ppm.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] There is little information on the chronic toxicity of arsine, although it is reasonable to assume that, in common with other arsenic compounds, a long-term exposure could lead to arsenicosis.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Arsine is a potent hemolytic agent, which is in line with its pathophysiological course of action.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] However, inhaling high concentrations of this agent is highly capable of inducing severe and direct pulmonary trauma.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] From a strictly clinical perspective, this typically manifests as chemical pneumonitis as well as non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] **Necrotizing Bronchitis:** This involves direct damage to the primary pulmonary conducting airways.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] In such instances, the smaller bronchi and bronchioles could potentially become surrounded by inflammatory cells and necrotic tissue.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] This damage to the epithelium can lead to focal lesions resembling bronchopneumonia.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Both manifestations are capable of leading to respiratory failure and death, often occurring at the same time as acute renal failure caused by hemolytic injury.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] It is classified as an extremely hazardous substance in the United States as defined in Section 302 of the U.S.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act (42 U.S.C.
[src:calcium-carbide/arsine] 11002), and is subject to strict reporting requirements by facilities which produce, store, or use it in significant quantities.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The pure material is colorless, while pieces of technical-grade calcium carbide are grey or brown and consist of about 80–85% of CaC2 (the rest is CaO (calcium oxide), Ca3P2 (calcium phosphide), CaS (calcium sulfide), Ca3N2 (calcium nitride), SiC (silicon carbide), C (carbon), etc.).
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In the presence of trace moisture, technical-grade calcium carbide emits an unpleasant odor reminiscent of garlic.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Applications of calcium carbide include manufacture of acetylene gas, generation of acetylene in carbide lamps, manufacture of chemicals for fertilizer, and steelmaking.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is produced industrially in an electric arc furnace from a mixture of lime and coke at approximately 2,200 °C (3,990 °F).
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] This is an endothermic reaction requiring 110 kilocalories (460 kJ) per mole and high temperatures to drive off the carbon monoxide.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The high temperature required for this reaction is not practically achievable by traditional combustion, so the reaction is performed in an electric arc furnace with graphite electrodes.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The carbide product produced generally contains around 80% calcium carbide by weight.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The carbide is crushed to produce small lumps that can range from a few mm up to 50 mm.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The impurities are concentrated in the finer fractions.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The CaC2 content of the product is assayed by measuring the amount of acetylene produced on hydrolysis.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] As an example, the British and German standards for the content of the coarser fractions are 295 L/kg and 300 L/kg respectively (at 101 kPa pressure and 20 °C (68 °F) temperature).
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Impurities present in the carbide include calcium phosphide, which produces phosphine when hydrolysed.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] This reaction was an important part of the Industrial Revolution in chemistry, and was made possible in the United States as a result of massive amounts of inexpensive hydroelectric power produced at Niagara Falls before the turn of the 20th century.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The electric arc furnace method was discovered in 1892 by T.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Willson, and independently in the same year by H.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In Jajce, Bosnia and Herzegovina, the Austrian industrialist Josef Kranz and his *"Bosnische-Elektrizitäts AG"* company, whose successor later became *"Elektro-Bosna"*, opened the largest chemical factory for the production of calcium carbide at the time in Europe in 1899.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] A hydroelectric power station on the Pliva river with an installed capacity of 8 MW was constructed to supply electricity for the factory, the first power station of its kind in Southeast Europe, and became operational on 24 March 1899.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is a calcium salt of acetylene, consisting of calcium cations Ca2+ and acetylide anions −C≡C−.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Pure calcium carbide is a colourless solid.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The common crystalline form at room temperature is a distorted rock-salt structure with the C2−2 units lying parallel.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] There are three different polymorphs which appear at room temperature: the tetragonal structure and two different monoclinic structures.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The reaction of calcium carbide with water, producing acetylene and calcium hydroxide, was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] This reaction was the basis of the industrial manufacture of acetylene, and is the major industrial use of calcium carbide.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Today acetylene is mainly manufactured by the partial combustion of methane or appears as a side product in the ethylene stream from cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Approximately 400,000 tonnes/y are produced by these routes (see acetylene preparation).
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In China, acetylene derived from calcium carbide remains a raw material for the chemical industry, in particular for the production of polyvinyl chloride.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Locally produced acetylene is more economical than using imported oil.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Production of calcium carbide in China has been increasing.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In 2005 output was 8.94 million tons, with the capacity to produce 17 million tons.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In the United States, Europe, and Japan, consumption of calcium carbide is generally declining.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Production levels in the US during the 1990s were 236,000 tons per year.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Commonly known as nitrolime, calcium cyanamide is used as fertilizer.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is used in carbide lamps.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Water dripping on carbide produces acetylene gas, which burns and produces light.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] While these lamps gave steadier and brighter light than candles, they were dangerous in coal mines, where flammable methane gas made them a serious hazard.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] The presence of flammable gases in coal mines led to miner safety lamps such as the Davy lamp, in which a wire gauze reduces the risk of methane ignition.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Carbide lamps were still used extensively in slate, copper, and tin mines where methane is not a serious hazard.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Most miners' lamps have now been replaced by electric lamps.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Carbide lamps are still used for mining in some less wealthy countries, for example in the silver mines near Potosí, Bolivia.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Carbide lamps are also still used by some cavers exploring caves and other underground areas, although they are increasingly being replaced in this use by LED lights.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Carbide lamps were also used extensively as headlamps in early automobiles, motorcycles and bicycles, but have been replaced entirely by electric lamps.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is sometimes used as a ripening agent, somewhat like ethylene gas.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] This use is illegal in some countries as, in the production of acetylene from calcium carbide, contamination often leads to trace production of phosphine and arsine.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In principle, these impurities can be removed by passing the acetylene gas through acidified copper sulfate solution, but, in developing countries, this precaution is often neglected.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is used in toy cannons such as the Big-Bang Cannon, as well as in bamboo cannons.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] In the Netherlands, a popular New Year's Eve tradition in rural areas is to use calcium carbide explosions to blow the lid or a ball off the top of a milk churn.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide, together with calcium phosphide, is used in floating, self-igniting naval signal flares, such as those produced by the Holmes' Marine Life Protection Association.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is used to determine the moisture content of soil.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] When soil and calcium carbide are mixed in a closed pressure cylinder, the water content in soil reacts with calcium carbide to release acetylene whose pressure can be measured to determine the moisture content.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] Calcium carbide is sold commercially as a mole repellent.
[src:calcium-carbide/calcium-carbide] When it comes into contact with water, the gas produced drives moles away.
